      "role": "assistant",
      "contents": [
        {
          "$type": "text",
          "text": "{\"workouts\":[{\"day_of_week\":1,\"workout_type\":\"Easy\",\"title\":\"Easy Aerobic Run\",\"target_distance_km\":3,\"target_duration_minutes\":24,\"target_pace_easy_sec_per_km\":450,\"target_pace_fast_sec_per_km\":450,\"segments\":[{\"segment_type\":\"Warmup\",\"duration_minutes\":3,\"target_pace_sec_per_km\":480,\"intensity\":\"Easy\",\"repetitions\":1,\"notes\":\"Start with a 3-minute brisk walk to ease into movement. No need to rush — let your body wake up gradually.\"},{\"segment_type\":\"Work\",\"duration_minutes\":18,\"target_pace_sec_per_km\":450,\"intensity\":\"Easy\",\"repetitions\":1,\"notes\":\"Run at a comfortable, conversational pace. You should be able to speak in full sentences. If you feel breathless, slow down or take a short walk break — that is perfectly valid.\"},{\"segment_type\":\"Cooldown\",\"duration_minutes\":3,\"target_pace_sec_per_km\":480,\"intensity\":\"Easy\",\"repetitions\":1,\"notes\":\"Ease back to a brisk walk for the final 3 minutes. Finish with light stretching of calves, quads, and hips.\"}],\"warmup_notes\":\"Begin with a 3-minute brisk walk before you start running. This primes your cardiovascular system and loosens your joints without stressing cold muscles.\",\"cooldown_notes\":\"Walk for 3 minutes after your run, then spend 5 minutes on gentle static stretches — calves, hip flexors, and quads are the priority after an easy run.\",\"coaching_notes\":\"This Monday run is your aerobic foundation session. At this early stage in your training, easy running builds the capillary density and mitochondrial capacity that everything else depends on. Using Daniels-Gilbert zones, your easy pace sits between 7:00 and 8:00 per km — aim for the middle of that range today. There is no prize for running faster here; the adaptation happens at a comfortable effort. Walk breaks are a coaching tool, not a failure.\",\"perceived_effort\":4},{\"day_of_week\":3,\"workout_type\":\"Easy\",\"title\":\"Midweek Easy Run with Strides\",\"target_distance_km\":4,\"target_duration_minutes\":35,\"target_pace_easy_sec_per_km\":450,\"target_pace_fast_sec_per_km\":390,\"segments\":[{\"segment_type\":\"Warmup\",\"duration_minutes\":3,\"target_pace_sec_per_km\":480,\"intensity\":\"Easy\",\"repetitions\":1,\"notes\":\"3-minute brisk walk, then ease into your easy running pace over the first kilometer. Let the body settle in.\"},{\"segment_type\":\"Work\",\"duration_minutes\":24,\"target_pace_sec_per_km\":450,\"intensity\":\"Easy\",\"repetitions\":1,\"notes\":\"Comfortable aerobic running at your Daniels-Gilbert easy pace zone — fully conversational effort throughout.\"},{\"segment_type\":\"Work\",\"duration_minutes\":4,\"target_pace_sec_per_km\":390,\"intensity\":\"Moderate\",\"repetitions\":4,\"notes\":\"4 x 20-second light accelerations (strides) at the end of the run. Not sprinting — just a smooth, controlled pick-up to roughly 5K effort. Walk or jog 40 seconds between each one. These teach your legs to turn over faster without stressing your system.\"},{\"segment_type\":\"Cooldown\",\"duration_minutes\":4,\"target_pace_sec_per_km\":480,\"intensity\":\"Easy\",\"repetitions\":1,\"notes\":\"Easy walk back to your start. Shake out your legs and do a brief full-body stretch.\"}],\"warmup_notes\":\"Start with a 3-minute walk, then run easy for the first kilometer before settling into your target pace. Never jump straight into faster efforts.\",\"cooldown_notes\":\"After your final stride, walk for at least 3-4 minutes and let your heart rate come back down before stretching. Light dynamic moves like leg swings work well here.\",\"coaching_notes\":\"Wednesday introduces a small neuromuscular element — four short strides near the end of your easy run. These short accelerations are not hard intervals; they are a low-stress way to begin teaching your legs the faster turnover you will need for a 5K finish. Think of them as waking your fast-twitch fibers up gently. The bulk of this run stays firmly in your Daniels-Gilbert easy zone. At 4km total, this fits comfortably within your 45-minute cap and your weekly volume.\",\"perceived_effort\":4},{\"day_of_week\":6,\"workout_type\":\"LongRun\",\"title\":\"Saturday Long Run\",\"target_distance_km\":5,\"target_duration_minutes\":42,\"target_pace_easy_sec_per_km\":460,\"target_pace_fast_sec_per_km\":460,\"segments\":[{\"segment_type\":\"Warmup\",\"duration_minutes\":3,\"target_pace_sec_per_km\":490,\"intensity\":\"Easy\",\"repetitions\":1,\"notes\":\"Begin with a 3-minute walk to prepare your body. Ease into running gradually — the first kilometer should feel almost too easy.\"},{\"segment_type\":\"Work\",\"duration_minutes\":36,\"target_pace_sec_per_km\":460,\"intensity\":\"Easy\",\"repetitions\":1,\"notes\":\"Run the full distance at a relaxed, easy effort. If you need a 1-2 minute walk break mid-run, take it — you are building time on feet, not running a race. The goal is to finish feeling like you could have kept going.\"},{\"segment_type\":\"Cooldown\",\"duration_minutes\":3,\"target_pace_sec_per_km\":490,\"intensity\":\"Easy\",\"repetitions\":1,\"notes\":\"Finish with a 3-minute walk and take a moment to appreciate completing your longest run of the week. Light stretching recommended.\"}],\"warmup_notes\":\"Walk for 3 minutes before you start. Saturday's long run is the most important session of the week — treat the warmup as non-negotiable.\",\"cooldown_notes\":\"Walk for at least 3-4 minutes after finishing, then spend 8-10 minutes on post-run stretching: hip flexors, hamstrings, calves, and lower back. Hydrate well and have a snack with carbohydrates and protein within 30-45 minutes.\",\"coaching_notes\":\"The Saturday long run is the cornerstone of your 5K preparation. Even at 5km, running for 35-40 minutes at easy effort builds aerobic base, strengthens connective tissue, and develops the mental resilience you will draw on at Parkrun. Using your Daniels-Gilbert easy zone (7:00-8:00 per km), aim for a relaxed, controlled effort the whole way. Walk breaks are fully acceptable — finishing this run strong and feeling good is more valuable than running every step. Over the coming weeks, this distance will grow steadily.\",\"perceived_effort\":5}]}"
        }
      ]
    }
  ],
